**Code Explanation:**

The code performs Out-of-Distribution (OOD) detection and generates a Pareto front plot to identify promising metastable TMD candidates for synthesis. 1. Data Loading and Preparation: It loads the full enriched dataset and the 90-sample elastic training dataset from Step 2. The 112 metastable candidates are identified as those missing G_vrh values. 2. Mahalanobis Distance Calculation: It computes the centroid and covariance matrix of the training population using two physically relevant features: d_band_filling and en_difference. The Mahalanobis distance is then calculated for each metastable candidate to quantify its distance from the stable training distribution. Candidates with distances in the top 10th percentile (> 90th percentile threshold) are flagged as chemically exotic. 3. Feature Preparation and Prediction: The features for the candidates are prepared exactly as they were for the training set (including handling missing DOS values and generating magnetic ordering dummy variables). The Random Forest model trained in Step 3 is loaded to predict the is_viable probability for each candidate. The predictions and distances are saved to a CSV file for use in the final prioritization step. 4. Pareto Front Visualization: A scatter plot is generated with energy_above_hull on the x-axis (to be minimized) and predicted_viability_probability on the y-axis (to be maximized). The points are styled by their crystal phase and color-coded by their chemically exotic status. To make the plot informative, the non-dominated points (the Pareto front) among the non-exotic candidates are explicitly annotated with their phase labels. Synthesis window thresholds (Probability > 0.7, Energy < 0.05 eV/atom) are also overlaid.

